my meme

  1. This is a set of static graphs about good or bad study scores, because I am a college student, so I am sensitive to scores. So I made this graph of the different performance of those with high scores and those with low scores
library(magick)
# bad score image
bad_score <- image_read("https://cdn.memegenerator.es/imagenes/memes/full/32/25/32250880.jpg") %>%
  image_resize("200x200!")

# good score image
good_score <- image_read("https://blog.prepscholar.com/hubfs/feature_score-1.jpg") %>%
  image_resize("200x200!")


# create good score text blank and give text
good_score_text <- image_blank(width=200,height=200,color="#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text="When i get good score\nfull of confidence\nLife is full of hope",
                 color="#FFFFFF",
                 size=20,
                 font="Impact",
                 gravity="center")

# create bad score text blank and give text
bad_score_text <- image_blank(width=200,height=200,color="#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text="When i get bad score\nFeel suffocated",
                 color="#FFFFFF",
                 size=20,
                 font="Impact",
                 gravity="center")


# append them together 
top_row <- image_append(c(bad_score_text,bad_score))
bot_row <- image_append(c(good_score_text,good_score))
good_or_bad_score <-c(top_row,bot_row) %>%
  image_append(stack=TRUE) %>%
  image_scale(400)

#save the file
image_write(good_or_bad_score , "my_meme.png")

My animated GIF

  1. This is a set of dynamic graphs about good and bad study scores. Compared with static graphs, dynamic graphs are easier to show the contrast between the expressions and even the mentality of those who get good grades and those who get bad grades, which can also reflect the mentality of a large part of the students nowadays

library(magick)
# bad score image
bad_score <- image_read("https://cdn.memegenerator.es/imagenes/memes/full/32/25/32250880.jpg") %>%
  image_resize("200x200!")

# good score image
good_score <- image_read("https://blog.prepscholar.com/hubfs/feature_score-1.jpg") %>%
  image_resize("200x200!")


# create good score text blank and give text
good_score_text <- image_blank(width=200,height=200,color="#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text="When i get good score\nfull of confidence\nLife is full of hope",
                 color="#FFFFFF",
                 size=20,
                 font="Impact",
                 gravity="center")

# create bad score text blank and give text
bad_score_text <- image_blank(width=200,height=200,color="#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text="When i get bad score\nFeel suffocated",
                 color="#FFFFFF",
                 size=20,
                 font="Impact",
                 gravity="center")


# append them together 
top_row <- image_append(c(bad_score_text,bad_score))
bot_row <- image_append(c(good_score_text,good_score))
good_or_bad_score <-c(top_row,bot_row) %>%
  image_append(stack=TRUE) %>%
  image_scale(400)




# use morph function to make it look better and also change the size
frame <- c(bad_score_text, bad_score,good_score_text,good_score)
score_gif_2 <-image_morph(frame)%>%
  image_animate(fps=5)


#save the file
image_write(score_gif_2 , "my_animation.gif")
